gland":"Kendal, Westmorland, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Parr","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Parr in Lancashire, or from residence at an enclosure (Middle English <i>parr</i>, Old English <i>pearr</i>).","German: from Middle Low German <i>parre</i> ‘parish, district, minister's house’; a metonymic occupational name for a parson or for someone who worked in a parsonage or manse. Compare   Pfarr  .","English: variant of   Pear   with the common late Middle English and early modern English change of <i>-er</i>- to <i>-ar-</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Pare","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Henri, Laurent, Normand, Fernand, Alphonse, Clermont, Elphege, Alain, Benoit, Gaston, Girard.","French (<b>Paré</b>): occupational name for someone who finished cloth, from the past participle of <i>parer</i> ‘to prepare’.","English: variant of   Parr  ."]},{"name":"Parman","meanings":["Americanized form of German <b>Parmann</b>: variant of   Parr  .","Possibly an altered form of German <b>Bärmann</b> (see   Barmann  ).","English: variant of   Pearman  ."]},{"name":"Porr","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ulrike, Gunther.","German:","metonymic occupational name for a grower or seller of leeks or other vegetables, from Middle High German <i>porre</i>, <i>pforre</i> ‘leek’ (from Latin <i>porrum</i>)."]},{"name":"Pfarr","meanings":["South German: from Middle High German <i>pfarr</i> ‘district, parish’ or <i>pfarre(r)</i> ‘parish priest’, hence an occupational name for a parson, or a topographic name for someone who lived near the parsonage."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":26,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Parr was born about 1356, in Parr, Lancashire, England, his father, John de Parr, was 22 and his mother, Matilda Leyborne, was 38. He married Elizabeth de Ros about 1383, in Kendal, Westmorland, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died on 3 October 1404, at the age of 49."},"et":{"about 1356–3 October 1404":"umbes 1356–3. oktoober 1404","1356–1404":"1356–1404","1355–1391":"1355–1391","1383–1408":"1383–1408","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","1385–Male":"1385–Surnud","1336–Male":"1336–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","3 October 1404":"3. oktoober 1404","1385":"1385","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","abt 1385":"umbes 1385","1391":"1391","1404":"1404","1336":"1336","1356":"1356","1355":"1355","1320":"1320","about 1356":"umbes 1356","about 1385":"umbes 1385","1408":"1408","about 1383":"umbes 1383","Parr, Lancashire, England":"Parr, Lancashire, England","Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England","England":"Inglismaa, United